This guidebook describes Altemps Palace (now Pallavicini-Rospigliosi) as the Bentivoglio Palace, indicating the change of ownership after Enzo Bentivoglio purchased it about 1619 on behalf of his brother, later cardinal Guido Bentivoglio (1579–1644), from Duke Giovanni Angelo Altemps (1587–1620).

From its founding in 1565 until the acquisition of the Borromeo Palace (ex-Gabrielli) in 1608, the Roman Seminary did not have a permanent home. Rather, the institution rented properties around the city of Rome. Although not specifically mentioned by the author, in this guidebook we can follow some of the peregrinations of the institution. For example, this entry mentions the Nardini Palace, which housed the seminary between 1593 and 1608. The previous location can also be identified on p. 380, where it is described as being in front of the San Macuto guglia (spire) during the period between 1585 and 1593 when the Roman Seminary rented two buildings, the so-called Case Spannocchi (Spannocchi’s Houses).

Church of Santa Maria sopra Minerva. Piazza della Minerva is the square in front of Santa Maria della Minerva, the church to which it owes its name. This entry repeats verbatim Panciroli’s text from 1625. An illustration of the square is provided on p. 384.
